#chap-header("3", [= The Dump Site], "Where the bodies are left")

The dump site is where Šauhahten disposes of the bodies after extracting
their souls. It is one of two field locations the party can discover during
exploration; the other is the ritual site. They can be found in either
order --- finding one makes finding the other easier, as trails connect
them.

== Getting There

The surviving peacekeeper's directions point the party northeast of Keshto,
into the thinning Weald where the Fog boundary draws close. The journey
takes the better part of a day on foot --- long enough to feel the
transition from settled land to wilderness.

#flavor[
  The forest changes as you move northeast. The canopy thins. The
  underbrush grows sparser but stranger --- pale shoots, fungi that should
  not grow this far from the Fog. The birdsong stops before you notice it
  has stopped. The air takes on a faint chemical tang that does not belong
  to any forest.
]

#attention[
  *Fog exposure:* The dump site is near the Fog boundary. The party is not
  yet in Dense Fog, but the proximity should be felt --- strange growth,
  unusual silence, the occasional wisp of Fog curling between the trees.
  If any mortal party members are present, note that prolonged exposure in
  this area is unpleasant but not yet mechanically dangerous. The ritual
  site is closer to the Fog and may trigger exposure rules.
]

The party can find the dump site by following the peacekeeper's directions
(*no check required* --- this is the minimum the adventure provides) or by
backtracking a trail from the ritual site (*Awareness D3*).

== The Scene

#aloud[
  You smell it before you see it. Not rot, exactly --- something drier, more
  clinical. The trail leads to a shallow ravine screened by deadfall and
  brush. Someone has piled cut branches over the opening. It is not a
  natural formation.

  Beneath the screen, you find the bodies.

  There are seven of them, laid out in a rough row. They are not
  decomposed --- they are _desiccated_, as if every drop of vitality has
  been wrung from them. Their skin is paper-thin, stretched tight over
  bone. Their eyes are open, and their expressions are not peaceful. They
  look as though something was pulled from them, and they felt every moment
  of it.

  The most recent body is perhaps a week old. The oldest could be months.
  Whatever has been done to them has slowed the normal process of decay to
  almost nothing.
]

== Investigating the Scene

- *Occultism D3:* These bodies have had their souls extracted --- not merely
  killed, but _emptied_. Whatever animating force a living person
  possesses, it has been drawn out by deliberate means. This is not the
  work of a predatory creature or a natural Fog phenomenon. Someone did
  this with knowledge and intention.

- *Medicine D4 or Alchemy D4:* The bodies show no signs of conventional
  violence --- no wounds, no poison, no disease. The desiccation is not
  physical dehydration but a side effect of the soul extraction: the body
  collapses inward once the animating principle is removed. The process is
  clean, almost surgical. Whoever did this has performed it many times.

- *Investigate D3:* The disposal is methodical. The bodies were carried
  here, not dragged --- there are no drag marks, but there are faint
  footprints (a single set, returning on the same path each time). The
  ravine was chosen deliberately: screened from casual observation, far
  enough from Keshto to avoid discovery, but accessible from a specific
  direction. The perpetrator comes, deposits a body, and leaves.

- *Awareness D4:* There is a trail leading away from the ravine in a
  direction _different_ from Keshto --- northeast, deeper into the Weald.
  The trail is faint but consistent: the same path used repeatedly. This
  leads to the ritual site.

#note[
  *What this site alone tells the party:*
  - Souls have been extracted from these people.
  - The perpetrator is methodical and has done this many times.
  - The bodies were brought here post-mortem --- this is disposal, not the
    site of the killings.
  - A trail leads deeper into the Weald.

  *What requires both sites:*
  - The full scope of the operation.
  - The method (alchemical, Mortefactor-derived).
  - The fact that neither site is where the perpetrator _lives_.
]

== Field Encounter

The area around the dump site is unnaturally quiet --- Fog-mutated wildlife
has learned to avoid it. However, the residual energy from the extracted
souls draws predators of a different sort.

#note[
  *Encounter: Fog-Touched Beasts.* This is likely the party's first combat
  in the adventure. Run it honestly but with a light hand on tactics ---
  these are beasts, not strategists. They attack the nearest target, use
  Pounce to close distance, and flee if reduced below half HP.

  *Composition for a party of 4:* 2 Fog-Touched Beasts (T1 Standard).
  Adjust by adding or removing 1 beast for larger or smaller parties.

  *XP:* 15 per beast (30 total for 2).

  See the Appendix for the Fog-Touched Beast stat block.
]

#attention[
  *System lesson for this location:* Investigation skills and reading a
  scene. The dump site teaches the party that skill checks yield useful
  information, that a crime scene tells a story, and that the threat they
  are facing is supernatural. If the party skips the investigation and
  focuses only on the combat, they miss the point --- gently redirect them
  to the bodies and what they imply.
]
